  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash arises from an assertion
in LoopVectorizationPlanner::computeBestVF():\n  assert((BestFactor.Width ==
LegacyVF.Width || planContainsAdditionalSimplifications(...)) && \" VPlan cost
model and legacy cost model disagreed\");\nDuring the reproducer, the VPlan cost
model chooses VF=8 while the legacy cost model chooses VF=4. The assertion only
permits disagreement if the VPlan contains additional simplifications over the
legacy model. The helper function planContainsAdditionalSimplifications is
supposed to detect such simplifications. However, it returns false, triggering
the assertion, even though simplifications exist (e.g., instructions skipped from
the cost model).\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe reproducer is minimized and
immediately aborts inside computeBestVF. The debug-only output is empty because
the process aborts before normal debug logging continues. Using the debugger we
inspected BestFactor (VF=8) and LegacyVF (VF=4). No other transformations
occurred before the assertion. This confirms the first transformation point is
the VPlan VF selection logic and the discrepancy between the two cost models is
not masked by prior IR changes.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nThe comment in
planContainsAdditionalSimplifications (lines 7288-7293) states: \"Return true if
the loop contains any instructions that are not also part of the VPlan or are
skipped for VPlan-based cost computations.\" Logical condition required:
(!SeenInstrs.contains(I) OR skipCostComputation(I)).\nBut the implementation
(line 7295) uses:\n  return !SeenInstrs.contains(&I) &&
!CostCtx.skipCostComputation(&I, true);\nThis is the opposite of the intended
logic: it only returns true if an instruction is neither part of the VPlan nor
skipped, excluding exactly the cases the comment says should qualify
(instructions that were skipped). Consequently, if the VPlan omits or simplifies
instructions but those instructions were also marked to be skipped for cost
computation (as happens due to precomputeCosts marking induction/exit/reduction
parts), the function incorrectly returns false. This suppresses the escape hatch
for legitimate VF disagreements due to simplifications and triggers the
assertion.\nThus, the bug is a logical operator error (&& instead of || plus
missing negation alignment) between specification (comment) and code.\n\n4.
Proposed Edit Point(s):\nFile:
llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp\nLines: 7292-7295\nChange the
predicate inside planContainsAdditionalSimplifications from:\n  return
!SeenInstrs.contains(&I) && !CostCtx.skipCostComputation(&I, true);\nTo:\n
return !SeenInstrs.contains(&I) || CostCtx.skipCostComputation(&I, true);\nThis
matches the documented intent: trigger 'additional simplifications' if an
original loop instruction is either not represented in the VPlan or explicitly
skipped from VPlan cost computations.\nNo other changes are required; assertion
logic remains correct.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe assertion failure is due to a
faulty condition in planContainsAdditionalSimplifications that misclassifies
simplifications, preventing legitimate cost-model divergence. Fixing the logical
operator restores correct detection of extra simplifications and allows the
assertion to pass when VPlan-based cost chooses a different VF for valid reasons.
Expected effect: opt no longer aborts on the reproducer; VF disagreement is
tolerated when simplifications exist, eliminating the crash while preserving
assertion semantics.\n",
